🔥 1. ABA Problem (VERY IMPORTANT)
👉 Problem Definition

CAS only checks:

“Is value still A?”

But it does NOT know if it changed in between.

🧪 Timeline Example
Initial: A

Thread T1 reads A
Thread T2 changes A → B → A

T1 does CAS(A → C) → succeeds ❌ (wrong!)

👉 T1 thinks nothing changed
👉 But system state actually changed → data corruption risk

🧠 Where This Happens?
Lock-free stack
Lock-free queue
Memory reuse scenarios
🛠️ Solution: Versioning (Stamped Reference)
✔ Use: AtomicStampedReference
import java.util.concurrent.atomic.AtomicStampedReference;

AtomicStampedReference<Integer> ref =
        new AtomicStampedReference<>(100, 0);

// Read
int[] stampHolder = new int[1];
Integer value = ref.get(stampHolder);
int stamp = stampHolder[0];

// Update safely
ref.compareAndSet(value, 200, stamp, stamp + 1);
🔁 Key Idea

Instead of:

A

We track:

(A, version)

So:

(A,1) → (B,2) → (A,3)

👉 CAS fails correctly now ✅

🧠 2. Memory Reclamation Problem
👉 Hidden Danger in Lock-Free Structures

In lock-based systems:

GC or locks protect memory

In lock-free:

One thread may delete node
Another thread still using it 💥

⚠️ Problem Scenario
Thread T1 reads node
Thread T2 deletes node
Thread T1 accesses deleted node → crash / corruption
🛠️ Solutions (Conceptual)
1. Hazard Pointers

Each thread says:

“I’m using this node—don’t delete it”

🧪 Idea
hazardPointer[threadId] = node;

Before deleting:

Check if any thread is using it
2. Epoch-Based Reclamation (Used in high-perf systems)
Divide time into epochs
Delete memory only when safe
👉 In Java?

You’re mostly safe due to GC, but:

Still relevant in high-performance libs
Used internally in JVM / Netty / Aeron
🚀 3. Lock-Free Queue (Michael–Scott Algorithm)

This is used in:

ConcurrentLinkedQueue
🧠 Idea

Maintain:

head
tail

Both updated using CAS

